[1] Case update
- Epidemiological situation
23 May 2018. Democratic Republic of Congo, Ministry of Health
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=76c24e86b4
[in French, machine trans., edited]

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 22 May 2018:
- a total of 58 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, including 30 confirmed, 14 probable, and 14 suspected;
- the investigations invalidated 8 of the 17 historical probable cases reported in Bikoro. As a reminder, these community deaths occurred in the weeks preceding the official notification that triggered the outbreak on 8 May 2018. As a result, these 8 cases were removed from the table;
- 9 new suspected cases, including 2 in Bikoro, 4 in Iboko, 3 in Wangata;
- 2 new cases confirmed in Iboko;
- 1 community death in Bikoro: body samples could not be taken because of the resistance of the community. This death was thus classified among the probable cases;
- 2 deaths from confirmed cases in Wangata 2 negative tests in Iboko

Remarks
-------
- Negative tests are systematically removed from the summary table.
- The category of probable cases includes all reported deaths for which it was not possible to obtain biological samples for laboratory confirmation.

News about the Ebola response
------------------------------
The 1st working session with ASSORBIKO (Association of Nationals of Bikoro), which is based, in Kinshasa was held.
- In view of the resistance reported in the community of Bikoro to cooperate with health professionals, the Ministry of Health, represented by the Director of the National Program of Communication for the Promotion of Health (PNCPS), Mr Raoul Kamanda, held a 1st strategic communication session with ASSORBIKO to join community efforts in managing the Ebola response in this country.
- This collaboration will contribute to the community relay strategy, aiming to involve all social actors (churches, associations, etc.) in raising [awareness of the disease and of the danger it poses], but especially, to adapt communication by making it accessible and translated into dialect "Ntomba" to better get closer to the population of Bikoro.

Incident at the Wangata treatment center
----------------------------------------
- Between Sun 20 and Tue 22 May 2018, 3 patients voluntarily left the isolation zone of Wangata Hospital (Mbandaka), supported by the Ministry of Health and Médecins Sans Frontières. The 1st patient, who was about to be cured, left the hospital on Sunday night. The other 2 left the facility with their families on the night of Monday to Tuesday: one of them died at his home, and his body was brought back to the health center for a safe burial, assisted by the teams from MSF.

The 2nd was brought back to the center on Tue 22 May 2018 in the morning and he died during the night. He was buried on Wed 23 May 2018, according to the proper procedures.

- In all 3 cases, as the Minister of Health explained, hospitals and Ebola treatment centers are not prisons. Even in times of epidemic, health professionals have a duty to respect the will and dignity of patients.

- There is much fear and confusion about Ebola in affected communities. The priority of the Ministry of Health is to reinforce community communication actions in order to sensitize the local population about the symptoms, the importance of going to the health structures quickly, and respecting the isolation measures, in order to stem the spread of the disease. The sooner patients are cared for, the greater their chances of recovery -- this also limits the risk of spread.

Use of a new experimental Ebola treatment
-----------------------------------------
- The Ministry of Health has asked the US authorities to test the mAB114 treatment during the current outbreak.
- mAB114 is an antibody derived from the research that Professor Jean-Jacques Muyembe of the National Institute for Biomedical Research has done on the basis of the serum of a survivor of the Ebola epidemic of Kikwit in 1995. This research began 3 years ago.
- In order to test the effectiveness of the treatment, they did tests on monkeys to which were injected with the Ebola virus. All monkeys treated with mAB114 were cured.
- The effective use of this antibody in the Democratic Republic of Congo will depend on the approval of the ethics committee of the School of Public Health of the University of Kinshasa.

--
