- 23 May 2018. 3 Ebola patients fled quarantine in Congo, sparking fears that the disease may spread.
Washington Post [edited] https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2018/05/23/three-ebola-patients-fled-quarantine-in-congo-sparking-fears-that-the-disease-may-spread/ [Byline: Siobhán O'Grady]

Health officials in Congo are anxious to contain the country's deadly Ebola outbreak -- which has already spread to an urban area -- before the situation gets any worse. But controlling the virus may have just gotten tougher.

On [Wed 23 May 2018], the Doctors Without Borders [MSF] mission in the Congolese city of Mbandaka announced that 3 Ebola patients there had left a hospital isolation ward and reentered the general population.

One patient left [Sun 20 May 2018], shortly before being discharged, and is still alive, according to the aid group. 2 others left overnight [Mon 21 Ma 2018]; one died outside of quarantine, and another was brought back to the hospital and died there.

"In all 3 cases, every effort was made by staff at the hospital to convince the patients -- and their families -- not to leave and to continue their treatment," Brienne Prusak, a press officer for MSF, as Doctors Without Borders is frequently known, said in a statement.

Eugene Kabambi, the World Health Organization's spokesman in Congo, told Reuters that 2 of the patients' families helped them leave the hospital [Mon 21 May 2018], then brought them to a church.

"It is unfortunate but not unexpected," said WHO spokesman Tarik Jasarevic. "It is normal for people to want the loved ones to be at home during what could be the last moments of life."

Now comes the challenge of determining who the patients may have come into contact with once they left the hospital in the city of more than 1 million people. There have been 58 confirmed, probable, and suspected cases of Ebola -- and 27 deaths -- as of [Tue 22 May 2018]. That number could dramatically increase if the disease were to spread widely in a major city.

When Ebola hit West Africa in 2014, some of the obstacles that impeded the medical response included lack of trust among communities dealing with outbreaks and religious practices -- such as washing the body of the dead -- that spread the disease, which is contagious through bodily fluids. Community outreach to religious leaders in particular helped familiarize communities with the proper safety protocols.

But lack of trust between patients and doctors is often the reason those sick with Ebola would attempt to evade treatment, which can be intimidating when it involves isolating them from their families and only interacting with medical professionals dressed in hazmat suits. In previous Ebola outbreaks, patients have also left the hospital despite doctors urging them not to.

MSF is warning against seeing "forced hospitalization" as the solution to the outbreak. "Patient adherence is paramount," Prusak said. "The quicker patients are admitted, the greater their chance of survival, and the greater the chance of limiting the spread of Ebola."

- 24 May 2018. 2 Congo Ebola patients attended church with 50 people before dying: MSF
Reuters [edited] https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-ebola-congo/two-congo-ebola-patients-attended-church-with-50-people-before-dying-msf-idUSKCN1IP1PT [Byline Stephanie Nebehay]

Two Ebola patients who fled a Congo hospital went to a prayer meeting with 50 other people, potentially exposing them all to the deadly virus, a senior aid worker said on [Thu 24 May 2018].

Both patients were vomiting and infectious and died hours after the prayer session in the port city of Mbandaka, Dr Jean-Clement Cabrol, emergency medical coordinator for Médecins Sans Frontières (Doctors Without Borders), said.

Democratic Republic of Congo is racing to contain an outbreak of the disease which spreads through contact with infected bodily fluids.

The 2 patients slipped out of an isolation ward at the hospital on Monday night [21 May 2018].

"The escape was organized by the families, with 6 motorcycles as the patients were very ill and couldn't walk," Cabrol told a news briefing in Geneva on return from the affected region.

"They were taken to a prayer room with 50 people to pray. They were found at 2 in the morning, one of them dead and one was dying. So that's 50-60 contacts right there. The patients were in the active phase of the disease, vomiting."

[Escape, elopement, voluntary leave -- whatever one wishes to call it, the departure of infectious Ebola patients from a treatment facility is an alarming development. Such actions endanger the general population and make contact tracing exponentially more difficult. Although MSF undoubtedly made every effort to dissuade patients from leaving the hospital, allowing them to do so directly contradicts the 1st of MSF's own "Six Pillars of Ebola Control": the isolation and care of patients. (http://www.msf.org/sites/msf.org/files/msf1yearebolareport_en_230315.pdf).

It is true that hospitals are not prisons, and MSF and WHO are not legal authorities. But this is precisely the role of government and civil authorities, to step in to this "grey zone" between individual rights and the necessity and duty to protect the general public. Otherwise, the situation could quickly degenerate into chaos and panic at all levels, from neighborhood vigilante groups to the suspension of commercial air flights in and out of the country. This is the 1st urban Ebola outbreak in the DRC, so the governmental and legal experience of other African Union countries -- in particular Nigeria, which quelled potentially calamitous small urban outbreaks during the 2014-15 West African epidemic -- may be helpful here.

If the Ebola treatment unit (ETU) is a ward or wing of a fixed hospital building equipped with electrical power, there may be other ways to facilitate communication and contact between patients and their loved ones. For example, the ETU established in the Jui Hospital outside of Freetown in late 2014-2015 by the Sierra Leone MOH and Chinese Beijing 301 Hospital teams was equipped with closed circuit TV monitors and 2-way speakers, permitting patients and staff to communicate with each other at all times, without requiring entry into the high-risk zone wearing PPE (personal protective equipment). - Mod.LXL]

******
[3] Border controls
23 May 2018. WHO says 9 nations mobilize to prevent possible Ebola spread
Lemon Wire, Associated press (AP) [edited] https://www.lemonwire.com/2018/05/23/who-says-9-nations-mobilize-to-prevent-possible-ebola-spread/

The World Health Organization's regional director for Africa says the agency is accelerating efforts with 9 countries neighboring Congo to try to prevent the spread of the current Ebola outbreak beyond its borders.

Matshidiso Moeti says teams are being deployed to assess preparedness and "immediate next steps" include boosting capacity-building, training, and resource mobilization.

The top 2 priority countries are Central African Republic and the Republic of Congo, near the epicenter of the outbreak. In the Republic of Congo, for example, WHO is working with government officials "to stop functioning" an active market on its side of the Congo River.

Moeti told a World Health Assembly session [Wed 23 May 2018], the 9 countries "have already initiated their readiness activities." The others are Angola, Burundi, Rwanda, South Sudan, Tanzania and Zambia.

